00:25.920 --> 00:27.524
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

00:36.320 --> 00:40.644
<i>HAZEL: I believe we have a choice in this
world about how to tell sad stories.</i>

00:40.800 --> 00:43.485
<i>On the one hand,
you can sugarcoat it.</i>

00:43.640 --> 00:46.086
<i>The way they do in movies
and romance novels...</i>

00:46.240 --> 00:49.642
<i>where beautiful people
learn beautiful lessons...</i>

00:49.800 --> 00:51.928
<i>where nothing is too messed
up that can't be fixed...</i>

00:52.080 --> 00:54.003
<i>with an apology
and a Peter Gabriel song.</i>

00:54.960 --> 00:57.247
<i>I like that version as much
as the next girl does,</i>

00:57.320 --> 00:58.481
<i>believe me.</i>

00:59.600 --> 01:01.329
<i>It's just not the truth.</i>

01:02.680 --> 01:03.806
<i>This is the truth.</i>

01:05.360 --> 01:06.361
<i>Sorry.</i>

01:13.120 --> 01:15.600
<i>Late in the winter
of my seventeenth year...</i>

01:16.360 --> 01:18.681
<i>my mother decided
that I was depressed.</i>

01:18.760 --> 01:19.841
(SIGHS)

01:20.520 --> 01:23.171
She just eats like a bird,
she barely leaves the house.

01:23.320 --> 01:24.845
I am not depressed, Mom.

01:25.000 --> 01:26.684
She's reading the same
book over and over.

01:26.840 --> 01:27.841
She's depressed.

01:28.000 --> 01:29.411
I'm not depressed.

01:29.560 --> 01:31.961
<i>The booklets and the websites
always list depression as</i>

01:32.040 --> 01:33.326
<i>a side effect of cancer.</i>

01:33.400 --> 01:34.890
(ALL CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY)

01:34.960 --> 01:37.201
<i>Depression's not
a side effect of cancer.</i>

01:39.720 --> 01:41.688
<i>It's a side effect of dying.</i>

01:44.360 --> 01:46.408
<i>Which is what
was happening to me.</i>

01:51.520 --> 01:52.567
(GIRL LAUGHING)

01:55.320 --> 01:57.368
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION)

02:04.880 --> 02:06.564
I may switch you to Zoloft.

02:06.920 --> 02:08.445
Or Lexapro.

02:08.600 --> 02:10.011
And twice a day instead of once.

02:10.160 --> 02:11.685
Why stop there?
Hmm?

02:11.840 --> 02:13.040
Really, just keep them coming.

02:13.064 --> 02:14.793
I'm like the Keith Richards
of cancer kids.

02:14.920 --> 02:17.366
Have you been going to that
support group I suggested?

02:17.520 --> 02:18.931
Yeah, it's not my thing.

02:19.080 --> 02:20.525
Support groups
can be a great way

02:20.600 --> 02:22.200
for you to connect
with people who are...

02:22.360 --> 02:25.125
Who are... What?

02:25.560 --> 02:26.721
...on the same journey.

02:26.920 --> 02:28.888
"Journey"? Really?

02:29.080 --> 02:30.160
DR. MARIA:
Give it a chance.

02:31.080 --> 02:34.402
Who knows, you might even
find it enlightening.

02:34.960 --> 02:36.166
(STRUMS CHORD)

02:37.040 --> 02:38.530
All right.

02:39.120 --> 02:40.406
Are you guys ready?

02:41.040 --> 02:43.725
We are gathered here today

02:43.880 --> 02:47.566
literally in the heart of Jesus.

02:49.480 --> 02:51.926
We're here with J.C.

02:52.080 --> 02:54.048
Who wants to share their
story with the group?

02:54.640 --> 02:55.641
I'm Angel.

02:55.720 --> 02:57.449
I have acute myeloid leukemia.

02:58.120 --> 03:00.600
Sid. Acute lymphoblastic
leukemia.

03:01.480 --> 03:04.723
Hi, I'm PJ.
Um, I have neuroblastoma.

03:04.880 --> 03:07.167
I'm Patrick.

03:07.240 --> 03:08.287
Testicular.

03:08.440 --> 03:12.126
HAZEL: <i>I'll spare you the gory
details of Patrick's ball cancer.</i>

03:12.800 --> 03:15.451
<i>Basically, they found it
in his nuts...</i>

03:15.640 --> 03:19.281
<i>they cut most of it out, and he
almost died, but he didn't die.</i>

03:20.400 --> 03:24.007
<i>So now, here he is,
divorced, friendless...</i>

03:24.160 --> 03:26.128
<i>living on his parents' couch...</i>

03:26.440 --> 03:30.331
<i>exploiting his cancer-tastic
past in the heart of Jesus.</i>

03:30.520 --> 03:31.681
<i>Literally.</i>

03:31.840 --> 03:35.640
<i>To show us that one day,
if we 're lucky.</i> ..

03:35.800 --> 03:38.804
<i>We could be just like him.</i>

03:39.640 --> 03:40.687
Who's next?

03:41.520 --> 03:42.567
(SIGHS)

03:42.640 --> 03:43.971
Hazel?

03:44.200 --> 03:45.611
(SIGHS DEEPLY)

03:48.520 --> 03:49.681
Um...

03:49.760 --> 03:51.000
I'm Hazel.

03:51.120 --> 03:52.690
Uh, thyroid, originally...

03:52.840 --> 03:54.683
but now with
quite the impressive

03:54.760 --> 03:56.569
satellite colony in my lungs.

03:56.640 --> 03:59.769
(STAMMERING)
And how are you doing?

03:59.840 --> 04:03.401
<i>Uh, you mean besides
the terminal cancer?</i>

04:04.720 --> 04:06.688
All right, I guess.

04:08.280 --> 04:10.362
ALL: We're here
for you, Hazel.

04:11.680 --> 04:13.728
Why don't I play another song?

04:15.880 --> 04:17.769
(PLAYING UPBEAT MUSIC)

04:22.880 --> 04:24.291
<i>(SINGING) Christ is our friend</i>

04:24.360 --> 04:26.203
<i>And he'll be there till the end</i>

04:26.360 --> 04:27.600
<i>Christ is our friend</i>

04:27.680 --> 04:29.967
<i>And he'll be there till the end</i>

04:30.160 --> 04:35.087
<i>Christ</i>

04:40.200 --> 04:41.770
Hey, sweet pea.

04:46.880 --> 04:50.168
So... was it awesome?

04:53.200 --> 04:55.567
"Yeah, Mom,
it was awesome!"

04:55.640 --> 04:57.165
(ENGINE STARTS)

05:01.560 --> 05:03.528
<i>HAZEL". And that was my life.</i>

05:04.040 --> 05:05.610
<i>Reality shows.</i>

05:06.040 --> 05:08.361
<i>Doctor's appointments.</i>

05:08.520 --> 05:11.888
<i>Eight prescription drugs,
three times a day.</i>

05:12.080 --> 05:13.730
<i>But worst, worst,
worst of all...</i>

05:15.200 --> 05:16.361
<i>Support group-</i>

05:16.520 --> 05:18.320
You cannot make me.
MICHAEL: Of course we can.

05:18.440 --> 05:19.566
We're your parents.

05:19.960 --> 05:21.325
Come on,
we've been through this.

05:21.400 --> 05:22.447
You need to go.

05:22.600 --> 05:24.728
You need to make friends,
and be a teenager.

05:24.880 --> 05:26.320
Mom, if you want me
to be a teenager,

05:26.344 --> 05:27.930
you don't send me
to support group.

05:28.080 --> 05:31.243
You gotta get me a fake ID
so that I can go to clubs...

05:31.400 --> 05:33.050
and drink gimlets and take pot.

05:33.120 --> 05:35.282
Uh, you don't "take" pot.

05:35.360 --> 05:36.441
(LAUGHS)

05:36.600 --> 05:38.960
Well, that is the kind of thing
I would know with a fake ID.

05:38.984 --> 05:41.351
(MICHAEL LAUGHS) Can you
just get in the car, please?

05:42.680 --> 05:43.886
(GRUNTS)

05:44.880 --> 05:46.530
(MIMICS GROANING)

05:46.920 --> 05:48.410
HAZEL: <i>And</i> so <i>I</i> went.

05:48.720 --> 05:51.963
<i>Not because I wanted to, or because
I thought it would help</i> me...

05:52.160 --> 05:55.130
<i>but for the same reason
I did anything these days.</i>

05:55.280 --> 05:56.281
<i>To make my parents happy.</i>

05:56.440 --> 05:58.640
I really don't understand
why I can't just drive myself.

05:58.760 --> 06:00.280
It's not like you're
gonna do anything.

06:00.354 --> 06:02.118
You're just gonna sit here
and wait again.

06:02.354 --> 06:03.451
Of course I'm not.

06:03.600 --> 06:07.241
No, I've got stuff to do.
I'm gonna do errands.

06:07.320 --> 06:08.367
Yeah.

06:08.480 --> 06:09.811
I love you.

06:09.960 --> 06:10.961
I love you, too.

06:11.080 --> 06:12.411
Have fun.

06:13.640 --> 06:16.166
HAZEL: <i>The only thing worse
than biting it from cancer...</i>

06:16.320 --> 06:18.482
<i>is having a kid
bite it from cancer.</i>

06:20.000 --> 06:21.286
Hey!

06:21.800 --> 06:23.768
Make some friends.

06:26.320 --> 06:27.321
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

06:27.920 --> 06:29.285
Oh, sorry.

06:29.440 --> 06:30.720
I'll take the stairs.
No problem.

06:30.744 --> 06:31.745
Thank you.

06:32.640 --> 06:33.926
(GRUNTS) Sorry.

06:35.480 --> 06:36.606
My bad.

06:37.400 --> 06:39.004
I'm sorry.
(CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY)

06:50.960 --> 06:52.405
Oh, my God.

06:59.320 --> 07:00.845
<i>PATRICK: So,
who would like to start?</i>

07:02.000 --> 07:05.004
Does anyone want to start?
Who wants to kick it off?

07:06.520 --> 07:08.010
Go ahead.

07:08.160 --> 07:11.323
I'm Beth. I have
spindle cell sarcoma.

07:11.480 --> 07:12.891
It's been an okay week.

07:14.240 --> 07:16.004
(BETH CONTINUES INDISTINCTLY)

07:29.000 --> 07:31.890
PATRICK: Isaac, I know that you're
facing some challenges right now.

07:32.040 --> 07:33.690
Do you want to share
with the group?

07:33.760 --> 07:35.046
Or maybe your friend, here?

07:35.520 --> 07:36.567
ISAAC: No, I'll share.

07:37.360 --> 07:38.850
Hey, guys. Uh...

07:39.200 --> 07:41.043
Hi, I'm Isaac.

07:41.200 --> 07:42.725
I have retinoblastoma.

07:43.200 --> 07:45.040
We had surgery on one eye
when I was younger...

07:45.064 --> 07:46.684
so this is a glass eye.

07:46.760 --> 07:49.280
And then I'm going in to the
hospital to have another surgery...

07:49.304 --> 07:50.400
to take out the other eye.

07:50.560 --> 07:52.927
So, after that surgery, I'm
just gonna be totally blind.

07:53.200 --> 07:56.000
But I'm lucky, because I have this
beautiful, smoking hot girlfriend...

07:56.024 --> 07:58.391
who's way out of my league.
Monica.

07:58.720 --> 08:03.248
And I have great friends like
Augustus Waters to help me out.

08:03.440 --> 08:06.205
So, that's what's up.
Thanks.

08:06.520 --> 08:08.124
ALL: We're here
for you, Isaac.

08:08.400 --> 08:09.606
Thank you.
(CHUCKLES)

08:10.520 --> 08:11.760
Your turn, Gus.

08:12.760 --> 08:13.966
Yeah, sure.

08:16.320 --> 08:18.926
Um, I'm Augustus Waters.

08:19.080 --> 08:20.764
I'm 18 years old

08:20.920 --> 08:24.811
and I had a touch of osteosarcoma
about a year-and-a-half ago.

08:24.960 --> 08:28.487
So, I've lost this baby
as a result.

08:29.400 --> 08:32.768
And, uh, now I'm part
cyborg, which is awesome.

08:32.919 --> 08:36.241
But, really, I'm just
here at Isaac's request.

08:36.400 --> 08:38.801
And how are you feeling, Gus?

08:39.120 --> 08:40.884
I'm grand, yeah.

08:41.080 --> 08:43.287
I'm on a roller coaster that
only goes up, my friend.

08:44.080 --> 08:46.560
Maybe you'd like to share
your fears with the group?

08:46.720 --> 08:48.131
GUS: My fears?

08:52.120 --> 08:53.326
Oblivion.

08:53.760 --> 08:54.761
PATRICK: Oblivion?

08:54.920 --> 08:56.126
GUS: Yeah.

08:56.280 --> 08:58.681
You see, I intend to live
an extraordinary life.

08:58.840 --> 08:59.841
To be remembered.

09:00.440 --> 09:01.720
So, I'd say if I have any fears,

09:01.744 --> 09:03.872
it would be to not do that.

09:05.840 --> 09:09.162
Would anyone else in the
group like to speak to that?

09:10.800 --> 09:12.086
Hazel?
(CHUCKLES)

09:12.680 --> 09:14.284
Unexpected.

09:16.640 --> 09:18.085
I just want to say
that there's gonna

09:18.240 --> 09:19.810
come a time when
all of us are dead.

09:20.320 --> 09:21.890
There was a time before humans

09:21.960 --> 09:23.610
and there's gonna
be a time after.

09:23.760 --> 09:26.080
It could be tomorrow, it could
be a million years from now.

09:26.120 --> 09:28.009
And when it does,
there will be no one left...

09:28.160 --> 09:32.484
to remember Cleopatra or
Muhammad Ali or Mozart...

09:32.640 --> 09:34.529
let alone any of us.

09:36.160 --> 09:37.525
Oblivion's inevitable.

09:37.720 --> 09:39.848
And if that scares you, then
I suggest you ignore it.

09:41.160 --> 09:44.004
God knows it's what
everyone else does.

09:46.240 --> 09:47.480
(EXHALES)

09:48.480 --> 09:51.370
Well, that's some good advice.

09:52.000 --> 09:56.688
And I like all this because it's
really nice to hear everybody...

10:05.080 --> 10:06.684
Thank you.
Mmm-hmm.

10:09.800 --> 10:11.325
Always.
Always.

10:14.680 --> 10:16.045
MONICA: Always.
ISAAC: Always.

10:17.360 --> 10:19.203
"Literally."

10:20.400 --> 10:22.000
I thought we were
in a church basement...

10:22.024 --> 10:25.242
but apparently we were literally
in the heart of Jesus.

10:25.400 --> 10:27.129
Oh, yeah.
(LAUGHS)

10:29.600 --> 10:30.647
What's your name?

10:31.040 --> 10:32.405
Hazel.

10:32.560 --> 10:34.210
No, what's your full name?

10:34.560 --> 10:36.449
Hazel Grace Lancaster.

10:42.120 --> 10:43.201
What?

10:43.360 --> 10:44.361
I didn't say anything.

10:44.440 --> 10:46.408
Why are you looking
at me like that?

10:46.560 --> 10:48.085
Because you're beautiful.

10:48.280 --> 10:49.327
Oh, my God.

10:49.400 --> 10:51.528
I enjoy looking
at beautiful people.

10:52.200 --> 10:53.880
(STAMMERING) See, I
decided a while back...

10:53.904 --> 10:56.121
not to deny myself the simpler
pleasures of existence.

10:56.280 --> 10:58.965
Particularly, as you
so astutely pointed out,

10:59.040 --> 11:00.320
we're all gonna die pretty soon.

11:00.400 --> 11:02.562
Okay, well, that's great.
But I am not beautiful.

11:02.760 --> 11:03.807
Hey, Gus.

11:03.880 --> 11:04.927
Hi, Lisa.

11:05.720 --> 11:06.721
ISAAC: I like it
when you say it first.

11:06.800 --> 11:08.360
MONICA: I like it
when you say it first.

11:08.384 --> 11:08.881
Okay-

11:09.080 --> 11:10.366
Always.

11:10.560 --> 11:11.925
Always.
(LAUGHS)

11:12.080 --> 11:13.570
What is with the "always"?

11:13.720 --> 11:15.131
"Always" is, like, their thing.

11:15.320 --> 11:17.926
They'll "always" love
each other, and whatnot.

11:18.720 --> 11:22.247
They probably texted "always" to each
other 14 million times this year.

11:25.800 --> 11:28.246
He's got to be hurting her boob.

11:29.120 --> 11:30.485
Let's go watch a movie.

11:30.640 --> 11:31.971
What?
Hmm?

11:32.120 --> 11:33.281
Huh?

11:33.600 --> 11:35.967
(LAUGHS) Um...

11:36.600 --> 11:39.649
I'm free later this week,
we could...

11:39.840 --> 11:41.285
No, I mean now.

11:42.120 --> 11:43.645
You could be an axe murderer.

11:43.840 --> 11:45.683
There's always that possibility.

11:45.960 --> 11:48.088
Come on, Hazel Grace.
Take a risk.

11:48.240 --> 11:49.287
I don't...

11:52.680 --> 11:53.681
Really?

11:53.800 --> 11:54.961
That is disgusting.

11:55.520 --> 11:56.521
What?

11:56.600 --> 11:58.967
What, do you think that
that's cool or something?

11:59.120 --> 12:00.400
You just ruined
this whole thing.

12:00.480 --> 12:02.130
The whole thing?
Yes, this whole thing!

12:02.320 --> 12:03.606
Oh, man.

12:03.880 --> 12:05.803
Ugh. And you were
doing really well, too.

12:06.280 --> 12:08.965
God! There's always
a hamartia, isn't there?

12:09.160 --> 12:11.322
And yours is even though
you had freaking cancer...

12:11.480 --> 12:13.360
you're willing to give
money to a corporation...

12:13.384 --> 12:15.591
for the chance to acquire
even more cancer?

12:15.960 --> 12:18.645
Let me just tell you that not
being able to breathe sucks!

12:18.840 --> 12:20.330
It totally sucks.

12:20.480 --> 12:21.641
"Hamartia"?

12:22.840 --> 12:24.365
It's a fatal flaw.

12:24.520 --> 12:26.045
Ah, a fatal...

12:26.320 --> 12:27.321
Hazel Grace,

12:27.400 --> 12:29.400
they don't actually hurt
you unless you light them.

12:30.200 --> 12:31.201
Hmm?

12:31.640 --> 12:33.130
I've never lit one.

12:34.040 --> 12:35.166
It's a metaphor, see?

12:35.320 --> 12:38.483
You put the thing that does the
killing right between your teeth...

12:39.880 --> 12:42.121
but you never give it
the power to kill you.

12:43.360 --> 12:44.486
A metaphor.

12:44.920 --> 12:46.410
(CAR APPROACHING)

12:49.400 --> 12:52.051
Hey, sweetheart.
Is it Top <i>Model</i> time?

12:54.640 --> 12:56.324
No. Uh...

12:56.520 --> 12:58.170
I've made plans
with Augustus Waters.

13:03.160 --> 13:04.764
(HORN HONKING) Whoa!

13:04.880 --> 13:06.480
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO)
Oh, my God.

13:06.504 --> 13:07.646
Ooh!

13:07.880 --> 13:09.769
Yeah, I failed my test
a couple times.

13:10.200 --> 13:11.326
You don't say.

13:11.560 --> 13:13.200
Actually, the fourth time
I took the test,

13:13.224 --> 13:14.714
it was going about
how this is going.

13:15.080 --> 13:16.844
And when it was over...

13:17.000 --> 13:19.207
the instructor looks over
at me, and she says...

13:19.400 --> 13:22.768
"Your driving, while unpleasant,
is not technically unsafe."

13:23.080 --> 13:24.081
Cancer perk.

13:24.160 --> 13:25.889
Total cancer perk.
(LAUGHS)

13:27.560 --> 13:29.722
So, tell me about you.

13:30.160 --> 13:32.891
Um, I was 13 when they found it.

13:33.600 --> 13:35.887
<i>Pretty much
worst-case scenario.</i>

13:36.360 --> 13:38.522
<i>Thyroid, stage four.</i>

13:38.680 --> 13:39.761
<i>Not much they could do.</i>

13:40.400 --> 13:42.243
<i>Which didn't stop them,
of course.</i>

13:43.360 --> 13:44.361
<i>Surgery-</i>

13:44.560 --> 13:45.766
<i>Radiation.</i>

13:46.240 --> 13:47.241
<i>Chemo.</i>

13:47.720 --> 13:48.926
<i>More radiation.</i>

13:51.280 --> 13:53.248
<i>All of which worked for a while.</i>

13:54.240 --> 13:56.971
<i>But, then stopped working.</i>

13:57.320 --> 13:58.321
(GASPING)

13:58.440 --> 14:01.250
<i>And then one day, my lungs
started filling up with water.</i>

14:01.440 --> 14:03.442
Nurse!
We need a nurse right now!

14:03.600 --> 14:04.806
<i>HAZEL: I couldn't breathe.</i>

14:04.880 --> 14:07.042
<i>No one could get it
under control.</i>

14:07.560 --> 14:09.449
You can let go, sweetie.

14:10.160 --> 14:11.400
(WHISPERING) Don't be afraid.

14:11.720 --> 14:13.160
<i>HAZEL: That should have
been the end.</i>

14:13.440 --> 14:14.965
(SOBBING) Oh, my God.

14:16.400 --> 14:18.164
HAZEL: <i>But then something
strange happened.</i>

14:18.240 --> 14:19.969
<i>The antibiotics kicked in.</i>

14:20.120 --> 14:22.202
<i>They drained the fluid
from my lungs.</i>

14:22.280 --> 14:23.406
<i>I got some strength back.</i>

14:24.440 --> 14:27.808
<i>Next thing I know, I found
myself in an experimental trial.</i>

14:27.960 --> 14:29.371
<i>You know, the ones
that are famous</i>

14:29.440 --> 14:32.284
<i>in the Republic of
Cancervania for not working.</i>

14:32.440 --> 14:33.805
<i>It's called Phalanxifor.</i>

14:33.960 --> 14:35.803
<i>It didn't work in over
70% of the patients...</i>

14:35.960 --> 14:38.406
<i>but for some reason
it's been working for me.</i>

14:38.680 --> 14:40.125
So, they called it
"The Miracle."

14:40.280 --> 14:42.160
Of course, my lungs still
suck at being lungs...

14:42.310 --> 14:44.711
but, theoretically, they could
continue to suck like this...

14:44.870 --> 14:46.961
for, I don't know,
a while maybe.

14:47.480 --> 14:48.970
So, are you back in school?

14:49.120 --> 14:52.920
I got my GED, so I'm
taking classes at MCC.

14:53.120 --> 14:55.441
Whoa! A college girl!

14:55.600 --> 14:58.001
Well, that explains
the aura of sophistication.

14:58.080 --> 14:59.081
Oh! Careful!

15:04.520 --> 15:05.521
Oops.

15:05.600 --> 15:06.931
(LAUGHING)

15:08.920 --> 15:11.446
Welcome to my humble abode.

15:17.520 --> 15:19.488
Uh, my folks call them
"encouragements."

15:22.000 --> 15:23.081
Don't ask.

15:23.520 --> 15:24.726
(LAUGHS)

15:25.160 --> 15:26.161
Hi, guys!

15:26.480 --> 15:28.130
Hey!
Augustus, hi.

15:28.320 --> 15:29.845
New friend?

15:31.280 --> 15:33.521
Yeah.
This is Hazel Grace.

15:33.680 --> 15:35.011
Hey. Oh,
it's just "Hazel."

15:35.200 --> 15:36.800
MR. WATERS: How's it
going, "Just Hazel"?

15:36.824 --> 15:38.044
Hi, Hazel, how are you?

15:38.320 --> 15:40.049
Yeah, we're going
downstairs. Bye.

15:40.200 --> 15:42.200
Nice to meet you guys. BOTH:
Nice to meet you, too.

15:49.360 --> 15:50.486
This is it.

15:50.640 --> 15:52.802
Augusto World.

15:52.960 --> 15:54.121
This is my room.

15:54.280 --> 15:55.725
Wow.

15:57.880 --> 15:59.882
It's an impressive collection.

16:00.040 --> 16:01.166
Yeah, I used to play.

16:01.360 --> 16:02.361
(CHUCKLES)

16:02.680 --> 16:04.330
Do you mind if I sit down?

16:04.520 --> 16:06.522
Yeah. Make yourself
at home.

16:07.720 --> 16:10.200
<i>Mi casa es tu</i> casa.

16:11.400 --> 16:12.401
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

16:12.480 --> 16:15.211
Sorry, the, um, stairs...

16:16.960 --> 16:18.644
...and the standing...

16:19.400 --> 16:21.402
Yeah, I understand.

16:22.560 --> 16:23.561
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

16:23.640 --> 16:24.846
Seriously, are you okay?

16:25.080 --> 16:26.206
Yeah, yeah.

16:26.360 --> 16:29.011
All right.
What's your story?

16:29.240 --> 16:31.163
I already told you.

16:32.240 --> 16:34.083
I was diagnosed when I was 13...

16:34.560 --> 16:36.560
No, no, no. Not your cancer
story, your real story.

16:37.760 --> 16:39.250
Your interests, your hobbies,

16:39.320 --> 16:40.731
your passions,
your weird fetishes.

16:41.080 --> 16:42.241
"Weird fetishes"?

16:42.400 --> 16:44.720
Think of something. The first
thing that pops in your head.

16:44.744 --> 16:45.791
Something you love.

16:47.360 --> 16:48.771
<i>An Imperial Affliction.</i>

16:49.080 --> 16:51.765
Okay. What's that?

16:51.920 --> 16:53.046
It's a novel.

16:53.240 --> 16:54.924
It's my favorite novel.

16:55.080 --> 16:57.003
Wait, does it have
zombies in it?

16:57.200 --> 16:58.201
Zombies? No!
(LAUGHING)

16:58.280 --> 16:59.520
Stormtroopers?

16:59.680 --> 17:02.411
No, it's not that
kind of a book.

17:02.760 --> 17:04.364
Okay, what's it about?

17:04.880 --> 17:06.119
Uh, cancer.

17:07.240 --> 17:08.241
It's about cancer?

17:08.400 --> 17:12.246
But not like that.
Trust me, it's amazing.

17:12.400 --> 17:15.131
The author, his name
is Peter Van Houten.

17:15.440 --> 17:17.920
He's the only person I've ever
come across in my life...

17:18.079 --> 17:21.402
who, A, understands what
it's like to be dying...

17:21.599 --> 17:23.762
but, B, hasn't actually died.

17:23.920 --> 17:25.285
Okay-

17:25.480 --> 17:27.960
I will read this horrible book
with this very boring title...

17:28.119 --> 17:30.646
that does not include
zombies or Stormtroopers.

17:30.800 --> 17:32.131
And in exchange...

17:35.120 --> 17:36.804
...you will read this.

17:36.960 --> 17:38.200
This haunting,

17:38.280 --> 17:40.601
yet brilliant novelization
of my favorite video game.

17:41.400 --> 17:43.164
<i>"Counterinsurgence."</i>

17:44.520 --> 17:45.567
(LAUGHS)

17:45.640 --> 17:47.802
Yeah, don't laugh.
It's awesome.

17:48.000 --> 17:50.480
It's about honor, and sacrifice,
and bravery, and heroism.

17:51.440 --> 17:54.887
It's about embracing
your destiny,

17:54.960 --> 17:56.246
and leaving a mark on the world.

17:56.320 --> 17:57.685
(CHUCKLING)

17:58.560 --> 18:00.324
HAZEL: Well, thank you.

18:00.480 --> 18:02.642
Wait, your hands are so cold.

18:02.800 --> 18:06.088
Well, they're not so much cold
as just under-oxygenated.

18:06.400 --> 18:07.845
Hazel Grace?
Hmm?

18:08.120 --> 18:09.804
I love it when you
talk medical to me.

18:10.520 --> 18:12.010
(BOTH LAUGHING)

18:18.360 --> 18:19.521
That's different.

18:21.600 --> 18:23.967
Did he give it to you?

18:24.680 --> 18:26.205
By "it," do you mean herpes?

18:27.160 --> 18:28.286
Wow.

18:28.440 --> 18:29.646
Yes, I did.

18:29.800 --> 18:31.529
It's a mother's dream.

18:32.400 --> 18:34.209
(LAUGHING)

18:35.200 --> 18:36.690
(CELL PHONE VIBRATES)

18:44.120 --> 18:45.360
(SIGHS)

18:46.560 --> 18:48.881
Hey, don't worry.

18:49.040 --> 18:50.724
Oh, my God, Mom.
I'm not worried.

18:50.880 --> 18:52.041
It's not a big deal.

18:52.480 --> 18:53.561
Yeah.

18:53.720 --> 18:57.008
We just hung out, it's not like
I'm waiting for him to call me.

19:07.360 --> 19:08.566
(SIGHS)

19:28.400 --> 19:29.970
(SIGHS)

19:36.760 --> 19:38.360
MICHAEL: <i>Is that</i> what... <i>?</i>
FRANNIE: Yeah-

19:38.439 --> 19:40.239
MICHAEL: Because I thought
those were peppers.

19:40.263 --> 19:42.206
FRANNIE:
Today, in China,

19:42.280 --> 19:43.440
International Goji Berry Day.

19:43.464 --> 19:44.930
(CELL PHONE CHIMES)
(LAUGHS)

19:45.000 --> 19:46.081
Isn't that great?

19:46.240 --> 19:47.446
MICHAEL: I like the color.

19:47.600 --> 19:48.601
FRANNIE: Mmm-hmm.

19:48.680 --> 19:50.523
This is the dry.
Uh-huh. Very good.

19:50.760 --> 19:52.410
They're good, right?
Mmm-hmm.

19:53.360 --> 19:56.728
So, do they eat a lot of goji
berries on Goji Berry Day?

20:00.440 --> 20:02.442
I did something
with the dessert...

20:02.600 --> 20:05.729
just to try to keep
the goji berry theme going.

20:05.880 --> 20:07.609
Because they're
an amazing antioxidant.

20:12.960 --> 20:13.961
MICHAEL: Well, I like it.

20:14.080 --> 20:15.570
BOTH: We should
do it every year.

20:15.720 --> 20:16.846
FRANNIE: Every year.
We should do it every year.

20:16.960 --> 20:17.961
FRANNIE: I know.

20:18.040 --> 20:19.769
I really do like these.
(CELL PHONE CHIMES)

20:21.600 --> 20:23.489
Honey, would you like
to be excused?

20:24.720 --> 20:25.801
What?

20:26.240 --> 20:27.480
(LINE RINGING)

20:31.080 --> 20:32.809
GUS: Hazel Grace.

20:33.000 --> 20:36.163
<i>Welcome</i> to <i>the sweet torture of
reading An Imperial Affliction.</i>

20:36.320 --> 20:38.607
<i>ISAAC: (SINGING) But now I'm
breaking all the rules!</i>

20:38.760 --> 20:40.171
Are you okay?

20:40.320 --> 20:42.243
<i>And now
I'm breaking all the rules</i>

20:42.400 --> 20:44.846
Uh... Me? Yeah,
I am excellent.

20:45.000 --> 20:47.162
I am, however,
with Isaac, and...

20:48.000 --> 20:50.844
Isaac, does Support Group Hazel
make this better or worse?

20:52.760 --> 20:54.364
<i>I've been wasting all my time</i>

20:54.480 --> 20:56.005
Isaac! Focus on me.

20:56.160 --> 20:57.286
<i>Been wasting all my time</i>

20:57.480 --> 20:59.369
How fast can you get here?

20:59.760 --> 21:00.761
Um...

21:00.840 --> 21:02.080
<i>Great. Well,
the door's open.</i>

21:02.280 --> 21:03.486
I gotta run. Bye.

21:03.880 --> 21:05.120
(LINE DISCONNECTS)

21:10.480 --> 21:12.164
Hello?

21:12.320 --> 21:14.049
Hazel.

21:14.200 --> 21:16.160
Isaac, Hazel Grace from the
Support Group is here.

21:17.240 --> 21:18.241
HAZEL: Hi.
GUS: Hi.

21:20.360 --> 21:22.522
Uh...
A gentle reminder...

21:22.800 --> 21:25.041
Isaac's in the midst of a
psychotic episode right now.

21:25.200 --> 21:26.486
You look really nice,
by the way.

21:26.680 --> 21:27.681
I like this color on you.

21:27.840 --> 21:29.285
Thank you.

21:29.440 --> 21:30.805
Isaac.

21:37.040 --> 21:38.280
Isaac, Hazel's here.

21:38.560 --> 21:39.846
Hey, Isaac.

21:40.000 --> 21:41.843
Hey, Hazel.

21:42.200 --> 21:43.565
(SNIFFLES)

21:47.560 --> 21:48.721
How you doing?

21:48.880 --> 21:51.451
I'm doing okay.
(SNIFFLES)

21:51.520 --> 21:54.364
It seems Isaac and Monica are
no longer a going concern.

21:55.360 --> 21:56.880
Oh, Isaac, I'm so sorry.
(ISAAC CRYING)

21:56.904 --> 21:58.064
Do you want to talk about it?

21:58.200 --> 22:01.249
No, I just want to cry
and play video games.

22:02.400 --> 22:04.440
However, you know, it doesn't
hurt to talk to him...

22:04.464 --> 22:07.528
if you have any sage words
of feminine advice.

22:07.720 --> 22:10.690
I actually think that his
response is fairly appropriate.

22:10.920 --> 22:12.410
"Pain demands to be felt."

22:12.600 --> 22:14.090
You're quoting my book.

22:14.760 --> 22:18.526
She said she wanted to break up
with me before the surgery...

22:18.680 --> 22:20.921
because she couldn't handle it.

22:21.080 --> 22:24.721
I'm about to lose my eyesight,
and she can't handle it.

22:25.080 --> 22:27.401
I kept saying "always" to her.
Like, "Always."

22:27.560 --> 22:29.927
And she kept talking over me

22:30.000 --> 22:32.002
and not saying it back, and...

22:32.760 --> 22:36.287
It was like I was gone
already, you know?

22:36.440 --> 22:37.726
HAZEL: You know,
sometimes...

22:37.880 --> 22:40.042
people don't understand
the promises

22:40.120 --> 22:42.248
that they're making
when they make them.

22:42.400 --> 22:43.401
ISAAC: I know, but...

22:44.400 --> 22:46.050
I feel like such a loser.

22:46.120 --> 22:47.281
I still have her necklace on.

22:47.440 --> 22:48.566
Take it off.

22:48.760 --> 22:49.966
Dude, take that off.

22:50.960 --> 22:52.610
Yeah.

22:52.760 --> 22:54.205
Here we go, man.
Here we go.

22:54.280 --> 22:56.123
(GRUNTS) I just want
to kick something.

22:59.080 --> 23:00.730
Don't hit that, don't hit that.

23:01.240 --> 23:02.241
Uh...

23:03.280 --> 23:04.805
Hit this.
Sorry.

23:05.960 --> 23:08.008
(EXHALING DEEPLY)

23:09.040 --> 23:10.485
(GRUNTING)

23:11.480 --> 23:12.481
(LAUGHS)

23:12.920 --> 23:14.410
I've been wanting to call
you for a few days now...

23:14.560 --> 23:16.120
but I've been waiting
until I could form

23:16.160 --> 23:18.040
a coherent thought about
An Imperial Affliction.

23:18.720 --> 23:20.085
(MUFFLED SCREAMS)

23:21.000 --> 23:22.047
One second.

23:22.120 --> 23:23.281
Isaac.

23:24.320 --> 23:25.520
(PANTING) Pillows don't break.

23:25.800 --> 23:27.484
You need to break something.

23:28.600 --> 23:30.125
Try this.

23:30.960 --> 23:32.769
The trophy?
Yeah.

23:32.840 --> 23:33.841
Are you sure?

23:33.920 --> 23:36.760
I've been looking for a way to tell
my father I kind of hate basketball.

23:36.784 --> 23:38.354
Go to town!

23:41.680 --> 23:43.045
(GRUNTS)

23:44.600 --> 23:46.011
Always!

23:46.440 --> 23:47.851
<i>An Imperial Affliction.</i>

23:48.000 --> 23:49.809
Yes. I'm so glad
that you liked it.

23:49.880 --> 23:50.927
(ISAAC YELLING)

23:51.000 --> 23:52.525
Yes, I did.
But the ending.

23:52.680 --> 23:54.205
I know.
It is rather abrupt.

23:54.360 --> 23:56.601
"Rather abrupt"? Are you kidding?
It's evil!

23:56.760 --> 23:58.649
I mean, I understand
that she dies...

23:59.120 --> 24:01.280
but there's an unwritten
contract between author and...

24:01.640 --> 24:02.687
Gus?
Yeah?

24:02.840 --> 24:03.841
Cool?
Sure.

24:04.000 --> 24:05.490
Between author and reader.

24:05.560 --> 24:07.449
And I feel like ending your book
in the middle of a sentence...

24:07.520 --> 24:09.363
violates that contract,
don't you think?

24:09.520 --> 24:10.601
Okay, yes.

24:10.680 --> 24:11.727
I know what you mean...

24:12.120 --> 24:13.610
but, to be completely honest,

24:13.720 --> 24:14.920
I think it's just so truthful.

24:15.480 --> 24:17.289
You just die in
the middle of life.

24:17.440 --> 24:18.840
You die in the middle
of a sentence.

24:18.864 --> 24:20.126
(ISAAC CONTINUES YELLING)

24:20.200 --> 24:22.282
And, I don't know...

24:22.480 --> 24:24.209
But I really would like to know

24:24.280 --> 24:26.487
what happens to everyone
after Anna dies.

24:27.880 --> 24:28.881
Like Anna's mother.

24:28.960 --> 24:30.405
Yes, and the Dutch Tulip Man.

24:30.560 --> 24:32.130
And Sisyphus the Hamster.

24:32.400 --> 24:33.811
Yes!

24:34.080 --> 24:35.161
(GRUNTS)

24:35.240 --> 24:37.641
Have you tried contacting
this Peter Van Houten fellow?

24:37.800 --> 24:39.689
I've written him
so many letters,

24:39.760 --> 24:41.250
but he's never responded.

24:41.400 --> 24:42.811
Apparently, he moved
to Amsterdam

24:42.880 --> 24:44.211
and became a recluse, and...

24:45.640 --> 24:47.563
Shame.
Yeah.

24:47.920 --> 24:48.921
Isaacâ€œ.

24:49.240 --> 24:51.208
You feeling better, buddy?

24:52.320 --> 24:54.243
That's the thing about pain.

24:55.520 --> 24:56.567
It demands to be felt.

24:56.760 --> 24:59.411
ISAAC: (PANTING)
I'll help you clean this up.

25:01.920 --> 25:03.763
GUS ON PHONE:
Hazel Grace.

25:03.920 --> 25:04.967
Augustus Waters.

25:05.080 --> 25:07.560
I cannot stop thinking
about this goddamn book.

25:07.720 --> 25:09.882
(CHUCKLES) You're welcome.

25:10.000 --> 25:11.760
However, we do need closure,
don't you think?

25:11.784 --> 25:13.370
That is exactly
what I was asking

25:13.440 --> 25:14.726
Van Houten for in my letters.

25:14.920 --> 25:16.285
But he never responded.

25:16.760 --> 25:18.205
Um, nope.

